# The Problem

Refs are not passed as props by default. If you try to put a `ref` prop on a custom component, it won't work – React reserves `ref` for its own use.

To expose a DOM node inside a child component to a parent, you need to **forward the ref** using `React.forwardRef`.

## Syntax

```jsx
const MyInput = React.forwardRef((props, ref) => {
  return <input ref={ref} {...props} />;
});

// Parent can now use:
<MyInput ref={inputRef} />
```

`forwardRef` takes a render function that receives `props` and `ref`, and returns JSX.

slides.codeSnippet:
import { forwardRef, useRef } from 'react';

const FancyInput = forwardRef((props, ref) => {
  return (
    <div className="fancy">
      <label>{props.label}</label>
      <input ref={ref} {...props} />
    </div>
  );
});

function Parent() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const focusInput = () => {
    inputRef.current.focus();
  };

  return (
    <>
      <FancyInput ref={inputRef} label="Name" />
      <button onClick={focusInput}>Focus Input</button>
    </>
  );
}
